TRUST DEEDS A trust deed is the form used to convey property to some person who is entitled to its proceeds or profits.,1,0,0,0,0,0
This form of deed is often used to secure the payment of a debt.,0,0,0,0,0,0
In some states they take the place of mortgages.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"Where the trust deed is meant to take the place of a mortgage to secure a debt payment, the property is deeded to a third party known as a ""trustee.""",0,0,0,0,0,0
"The trustee in this case is the agent for debtor and creditor, and he must act impartially.",1,1,1,1,1,1
The trust deed specifies the character of the debt to be secured.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"In case of failure to pay the debt as agreed on, the trustee may, if so warranted, sell the property, and pay the obligation from the proceeds.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"The grantor in a trust deed, if not stipulated to the contrary, is entitled to all the rents and profits of the property; for it remains virtually his, until he has failed to fill his contract.",1,1,0,1,1,0
"When the indebtedness secured by the trust deed has been paid, the trustee must at once execute a paper known to law as a Release Deed.",1,0,0,0,0,0
