"HOW TO PREPARE A CHECK A check may be defined to be ""a written order on a bank directing it to pay a certain sum of money to the person named in the check or to his order, and signed by a depositor.""",1,1,1,1,1,1
"So long as the purpose is clearly conveyed in the writing no particular form of words is necessary, nor need the paper on which the check is written be the regular printed form properly filled in.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"The ""drawer"" is the one who makes the check.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"The ""payee"" is the one for whom the check is made.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"In making a check, the best plan is to fill out the stub first, and from the data on it make out the check.",1,0,0,0,0,0
This tends to accuracy.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Be sure to number your check, beginning with I.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Be sure that the number on the stub is the same as on the check.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"A person having money in bank and wishing to draw for his own use, makes his check payable to ""self"" or to ""cash.""",1,1,1,1,1,1
Usual form of check:            First National Bank.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"27             Kingston, Vt., Oct. 13, 1910.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Pay to order of John Smith       Seventy-five 75/100  ------ dollars.,0,0,0,0,0,0
$75.75               George F. Brown.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"It is proper form to specify on the face of the check the purpose for which it is given, but while this is permissible it is not usual.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Write the amount of the check first in words then in figures.,0,0,0,0,0,0
This makes more certain the amount.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Always begin first word of amount close to left-hand side of check; when the whole sum is written down draw a heavy stroke along the line to the word ""dollars.""",0,0,0,0,0,0
"When a check is made payable to John Smith or order, John Smith must sign his name on the back of the check--left-hand end and about an inch from the top.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Never sign a check until you are ready to collect, or to bank it.",1,0,0,0,0,0
The payee can endorse the check to another by writing on the back as follows:       Pay to the order of                Thomas Brown.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"A check payable to ""bearer"" may be negotiated by any one.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"When such checks are presented by a stranger, at the bank of the maker, the paying teller always insists that the stranger be identified.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Never make a check payable to ""bearer"" if it can be avoided.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Sometimes checks are dated ahead, for reasons satisfactory to the maker and payee.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"A check drawn on August 5th, but dated August 20th cannot be collected till the latter date.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Never date a check ahead unless you are positive that you will have the money in bank to meet it on the day named.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"Never, if you can avoid it in trade, receive a post-dated check.",1,0,0,0,0,0
