"Treasury notes or ""greenbacks.""",0,0,0,0,0,0
BANK NOTES A national bank note is the guaranteed promise of some national bank to pay coin or its equivalent to any one presenting the note at the bank and asking to have the exchange made.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"This exchange is called ""redeeming.""",0,0,0,0,0,0
"If you examine a bank bill you will notice that it is drawn much like an ordinary business ""demand"" note, made payable to ""bearer,"" and signed by the bank president and cashier.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"For every dollar of its own sent out in the form of a bill by a national bank, the Government holds a dollar of the bank's collateral to guarantee the redemption of the note if the bank should fail.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"National bank notes are received in all business transactions, because they are secured by the Government, yet there are cases in which even the Government will not receive them in payment of a claim, nor pay them out itself.",1,0,0,0,0,0
All import duties must be paid in gold.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The Government pays the interest on its own bonds in gold.,1,0,0,0,0,0
The Bureau of Engraving and Printing--a department of the United States Treasury--makes and prints all the national bank notes.,0,0,0,0,0,0
On all these notes the names of the United States Treasurer and the United States Register appear.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The names look like signatures, but they are facsimilies and are printed with the note.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"The notes are printed on specially prepared paper, to imitate which is regarded as a counterfeit.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Soiled and worn out bank notes may be exchanged for fresh ones at the Treasury Department.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"""GREENBACKS"" Greenbacks are treasury notes.",0,0,0,0,0,0
The name comes from the color in which they first appeared in the years of our Civil War.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The treasury note is really an engraved promissory note of the United States Government made payable to the bearer, and bearing the signatures of the Treasurer and Register of the Treasury.",0,0,0,0,0,0
These notes are issued in denominations of from five to ten thousand dollars.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Formerly there were one and two-dollar treasury notes issued, and we still find some of these ""old-timers"" in circulation.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"There are so many treasury notes in circulation that the Government, vast though its bullion and coin reserves are, could not redeem them if presented at once.",1,0,0,0,0,0
The treasury note is a legal tender for any amount of indebtedness.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The Government prints the following guarantee on every treasury note: ""This note is, by law, to be considered as good as coin.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Any one to whom you pay it must reckon it as equivalent to a dollar (or face value in dollars) in value.""",1,0,0,0,0,0
"TREASURY CERTIFICATES The treasury certificate is, in form, very much like the treasury note, and it bears the signatures of the same officers.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Treasury certificates are of two kinds, gold and silver.",0,0,0,0,0,0
The gold certificates are printed in yellow.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The silver certificates are light black and white.,0,0,0,0,0,0
